# BL 500 Solution Walk-Through

## PNG File
This challenge stars out with the file named [flag](https://github.com/SocialGeeks/hackerschallenge2016/blob/master/bl/500/flag?raw=true "flag") which contains a PNG format image:

![alt text](https://github.com/SocialGeeks/hackerschallenge2016/blob/master/bl/500/flag?raw=true "flag")

Inspecting the file turns up a little more than just an image.  At the end of every PNG file is an IEND chuck followed by a 4 byte chunk CRC. If we search for the IEND marker we see that there is a lot of data appended on to the end of the file, moreover we can see the 'ELF' signature. 

```
00020130: dc95 683a 5b6f 23d4 375a a72a 0420 0001  ..h:[o#.7Z.*. ..
00020140: 0840 0002 1080 0004 5e91 c0ff 070e fb4a  .@......^......J
00020150: daa1 d57b 9e00 0000 0049 454e 44ae 4260  ...{.....IEND.B`
00020160: 827f 454c 4601 0101 0000 0000 0000 0000  ..ELF...........
00020170: 0002 0028 0001 0000 0020 8300 0034 0000  ...(..... ...4..
00020180: 0038 4300 0002 0400 0534 0020 0008 0028  .8C......4. ...(
00020190: 001f 001c 0001 0000 70ac 4000 00ac c000  ........p.@.....
```
Extracting this extraneous data from offset `00020161` on into its own file and then running the `file` command confirms our suspicion.

```
plum$ file flag_extra 
flag_extra: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, ARM, EABI5 version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib/ld-linux-armhf.so.3, for GNU/Linux 2.6.26, BuildID[sha1]=a55b3615f4979e28e73199eba4f42d28aef31eec, not stripped
```

## ELF binary

From the output we see the executable is built for a 32-bit ARM system. Running strings on the binary didn't turn up much so let’s take a quick look at it in a disassembler.  The following output is from the main function as disassembled in Ida Pro.  Hopper Disassembler is another option and will provide much the same output, or in a pinch `objdump -d` works too.

```assembly_x86
.text:0000BDE8 ; int __cdecl main(int argc, const char **argv, const char **envp)
.text:0000BDE8                 EXPORT main
.text:0000BDE8 main                                    ; DATA XREF: _start+20o
.text:0000BDE8                                         ; .text:off_8354o
.text:0000BDE8                 STMFD   SP!, {R11,LR}
.text:0000BDEC                 ADD     R11, SP, #4
.text:0000BDF0                 MOV     R0, #0x47       ; c
.text:0000BDF4                 BL      putchar
.text:0000BDF8                 MOV     R0, #'o'        ; c
.text:0000BDFC                 BL      putchar
.text:0000BE00                 MOV     R0, #'o'        ; c
.text:0000BE04                 BL      putchar
.text:0000BE08                 MOV     R0, #'d'        ; c
.text:0000BE0C                 BL      putchar
.text:0000BE10                 MOV     R0, #' '        ; c
.text:0000BE14                 BL      putchar
.text:0000BE18                 MOV     R0, #'j'        ; c
.text:0000BE1C                 BL      putchar
.text:0000BE20                 MOV     R0, #'o'        ; c
.text:0000BE24                 BL      putchar
.text:0000BE28                 MOV     R0, #'b'        ; c
.text:0000BE2C                 BL      putchar
.text:0000BE30                 MOV     R0, #' '        ; c
.text:0000BE34                 BL      putchar
.text:0000BE38                 MOV     R0, #'f'        ; c
.text:0000BE3C                 BL      putchar
.text:0000BE40                 MOV     R0, #'i'        ; c
.text:0000BE44                 BL      putchar
.text:0000BE48                 MOV     R0, #'n'        ; c
```

Here we see a string being written to stdout one character at a time (presumably to avoid producing easily identifiable strings in the binary). To see what the string says we have a few options we can
 * Read the disassembly line by line and build the string by hand
 * Find an ARM processor (a Raspberry Pi would work here) or emulator and run the program to see what it outputs
 * Script the process of extracting the string

For this particular case it isn't too hard to deduce the string from examining the binary however since we'll need a more efficient way to do this in the future I'm going to explain how to extract the string using a python script.

We are going to exploit a nice property of the ARM 32-bit instruction set and that is that every instruction is exactly 4 bytes. If you recall from the output above every other instruction moves `MOV` one character into register `R0`. Thus, every 8th byte should be a character in the string. Given a starting address we can take every 8th byte until the move instructions stop. The exact byte that signifies a `MOV` instruction is 0xE3 which should be the last byte in the 4 byte instruction. So we'll take one character then skip 8 bytes as long as the 4th byte in the 8 byte set is 0xE3. I've thrown the follow python script together to do just that.

```python
import sys


def extractString(binary):
        out =''
        block = binary.read(8)
        while len(block) == 8 and block[3] == chr(0xE3):
                out += block[0]
                block = binary.read(8)
        return out

if __name__ == "__main__":
        if len(sys.argv) > 2:
                with open(sys.argv[1], 'rb') as binary:
                        output = ''
                        for offset in sys.argv[2:]:
                                binary.seek(int(offset,16))
                                output += extractString(binary)
                        print output
        else:
                print "Usage: %s binary [hex_offsets]"
```

Now we need to know the offset in the raw file. from the disassembly dump we see the first `MOV` in the main function starts off at offset `0000BDF0` but that is the virtual offset and not the raw offset in the file.  To find out what the difference between the two is we can run `objdump -h file` (Linux only, OSX's version isn't that great) looking for the `.text` section.

```
Sections:
Idx Name          Size      VMA       LMA       File off  Algn
  0 .interp       00000019  00008134  00008134  00000134  2**0
                  CONTENTS, ALLOC, LOAD, READONLY, DATA
...
...
...
 13 .text         00003d80  00008320  00008320  00000320  2**2
                  CONTENTS, ALLOC, LOAD, READONLY, CODE
```

From this we read that the .text sections virtual address starts at 0008320 and it starts in the file at 0000320 so to find the address in the file we just need to adjust the virtual address by -0x8000.  Thus, the address to use in our script to extract the string from the main function would be 3df0 (0000bdf0 - 00008000)

```
plum$ python string_extract.py flag_extra 3df0
Good job finding my first program, but your adventure has just begun...
```

Lovely, it seems we need to dig a little deeper.  Looking back at the binary in the disassembly we can see a number of exported functions all named libc_so_x where x is 0 to 8.  Inspecting these functions shows that they do a similar trick of building a string one byte at a time. But that's no problem now that we have our script.  We simply find the virtual addresses where each function starts building the string, subtract the offset then run our script passing it all the address to see what it says. 

```
plum$ python string_extract.py flag_extra 3dc bf0 1404 1c18 242c 2c40 3454 3c64
```

Redirecting the output of the above commands to a file give us the next layer. Now we have a new buffer to play with although it is in string form, we'll need to convert it back into a binary.
```
xxd -r string_output > raw_output
```
## Rubber Ducky
Let's see what we have
```
plum$ file raw_output
raw_output: data
```

Nothing, running `strings` didn't return anything and examining the buffer manually didn't tell me much either. The file didn't have a recognizable magic header and `00ff 00ff 00ff 00eb` wasn't much to go on.

Admittedly I was stuck here on this puzzle for 2 days until they posted a hint. 
> One's never alone...

I didn't feel that helped out much at first and was still rather frustrated. That is until I came across a Google search for the book 
[One is Never Alone with a Rubber Duck: Douglas Adams’s Absurd Fictional Universe](https://www.amazon.com/One-Never-Alone-Rubber-Duck/dp/1443823635)

The Douglas Adam reference had to be more than coincidence.  Could this be hinting at the USB rubber ducky I've heard Jason E. Street talk so much about? For those like me that weren't familiar with the USB rubber ducky it is a USB stick that when plugged in can mimic a keyboard and send preconfigured keystrokes to a computer.  The attacker writes a ducky script, compiles it the uploads it to the USB.  Looking at a few of these scripts I found they often start with the bytes `00ff 00ff 00ff 00eb`

I even found a [decoder here](https://ducktoolkit.com/decoder/) which gladly accepted my raw output and returned the following:

```
DELAY
DELAY
terminalDELAY
DELAY
username:541n7c0npassword:E4k3pD2Wydnt75rtt7zbWsKpassword:XpS2gV7NTQzCmMFpsxKfZ5Pcurl --user username:password http://www.gr3yR0n1n.com/ctf/541n7c0n/bl5/index.php --data "GetFlag=password"DELAY
g
```

## Some special hardware I know little about
I quickly surmised that I need to connect to that URL using the given username and password. It only took a few more tries to realize I also needed to provide "GetFlag=XpS2gV7NTQzCmMFpsxKfZ5P" as my POST body to receive the following response:

Ugh, apparently this is a series of instruction to push to some device @gr3yR0n1n was wearing on his wrist. I only knew this because one of the earlier BL challenges produced similar output.  Luckily, I didn't need his help on the last one and I wasn't going to wait until I saw him again to solve this one.  It's easy to see that the above data is in hex. I had a simple script for turning that back into raw data and just like the pervious challenge, there were some easy to read strings in there.

```python
import sys

if __name__ == "__main__":
	if len(sys.argv) > 1:
		with open(sys.argv[1], 'rb') as bus:
			for line in bus.readlines():
				print line[1:].strip().decode('hex')
	else:
		print "Usage: %s bus_file"
```
